VALUES
(43, 12, 40, 23, 6, 10, 10, 'that they should not see with their eyes', 'Connection of Blindness and Hardening', 'Both passages emphasize the themes of blindness and hardening of the heart, indicating a divine action that prevents understanding and conversion. The phrases about not seeing or understanding are closely aligned, illustrating a shared message about spiritual blindness.', 'theme', 0.643, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 40, 40, 13, 13, 15, 'that they should not see with their eyes', 'Connection of Spiritual Blindness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness and hardness of heart, illustrating how people fail to see and understand the truth. The phrases about not seeing or understanding are echoed in both texts, highlighting the consequences of this condition.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 40, 42, 8, 10, 10, NULL, 'Spiritual Blindness and Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness, where individuals are unable to see or understand divine truths. John 12:40 speaks of God blinding their eyes, while Luke 8:10 highlights that seeing they might not see, illustrating a similar concept of incomprehension.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 40, 41, 4, 12, 12, 'that they should not see with their eyes', 'Connection of Spiritual Blindness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness and lack of understanding. They highlight that despite seeing and hearing, individuals do not perceive or comprehend, preventing conversion and healing.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 40, 23, 57, 18, 19, 'I should heal them', 'Healing and Understanding Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing, with John 12:40 highlighting the hindrance to understanding and conversion, while Isaiah 57:18-19 speaks of God''s willingness to heal and restore. This connection highlights the contrast between spiritual blindness and the promise of healing.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 40, 28, 6, 1, 1, 'heal them', 'Healing and Restoration Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing and restoration. John 12:40 speaks of a condition that prevents healing, while Hosea 6:1 offers a promise of healing after returning to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 40, 5, 29, 4, 4, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Blindness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual blindness and lack of understanding. They highlight that the Lord has not given the people the ability to perceive or hear, resulting in their inability to be converted and healed.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 41, 23, 6, 1, 5, 'saw his glory', 'Vision of God''s Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeing God''s glory. Both passages emphasize the divine revelation experienced by Isaiah and the acknowledgment of Jesus'' glory.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 41, 23, 6, 9, 10, 'saw his glory', 'Connection of Vision and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeing and understanding. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the people''s inability to perceive the truth, as Isaiah speaks of their closed eyes and ears, while John notes that Isaiah saw the glory of Christ.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 41, 43, 1, 14, 14, 'his glory', 'Connection of Glory in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize ''his glory,'' linking the vision of Isaiah with the incarnation of the Word. This connection highlights the continuity of divine revelation through the recognition of glory.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 41, 43, 5, 39, 39, 'spake of him', 'Connection of Testimony and Vision', 'Both passages emphasize the act of witnessing and testifying. In John 12:41, Isaiah''s vision of glory connects to the scriptures in John 5:39, which testify of Jesus. This connection highlights the importance of recognizing divine revelation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 41, 47, 4, 6, 6, 'his glory', 'Connection of Glory in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of glory as both passages reference the glory of God revealed through Jesus Christ. John 12:41 mentions seeing His glory, while 2 Corinthians 4:6 speaks of the knowledge of the glory of God in the face of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 41, 2, 33, 18, 23, 'his glory', 'Connection of Divine Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine glory as both passages reference the visibility of God''s glory. In John 12:41, the glory seen by Isaiah is linked to the glory that Moses desired to see in Exodus 33:18-23.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 41, 42, 24, 27, 27, 'his glory', 'Connection of Prophetic Revelation', 'Both passages emphasize the revelation of Jesus through the scriptures. John highlights Isaiah''s vision of Christ''s glory, while Luke describes Jesus explaining the scriptures concerning himself.', 'prophecy', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 42, 23, 51, 7, 7, NULL, 'Fear of Reproach', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear of societal rejection. Both passages emphasize the struggle between belief and the fear of reproach from others.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 42, 43, 7, 13, 13, NULL, 'Fear of Confession', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of openly confessing belief in Jesus due to social repercussions. In John 12:42, the fear of being put out of the synagogue is highlighted, while John 7:13 notes that no one spoke openly for fear of the Jews.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 42, 43, 9, 22, 22, 'put out of the synagogue', 'Fear of Confession', 'Both passages emphasize the fear of being put out of the synagogue for confessing faith in Christ. This connection highlights the pressure faced by believers from the Jewish leaders, illustrating a common theme of fear and social consequences.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 42, 20, 29, 25, 25, NULL, 'Fear of Man and Trust', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear influencing belief. In John 12:42, fear of the Pharisees prevents confession of faith, while Proverbs 29:25 states that ''the fear of man bringeth a snare.'' Both passages emphasize the importance of trusting in the Lord over succumbing to societal pressures.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 42, 40, 10, 32, 32, 'confess him', 'Confession and Belief Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of confession in both passages. John 12:42 discusses the fear of confessing belief due to social repercussions, while Matthew 10:32 emphasizes the importance of confessing faith openly for divine acknowledgment.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 42, 23, 66, 5, 5, 'put out of the synagogue', 'Fear of Exclusion for Belief', 'This connection highlights the fear of being cast out for faith. Both passages emphasize the tension between belief in God and social ostracism.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 42, 40, 26, 69, 75, 'did not confess him', 'Fear of Confession', 'This connection highlights the theme of fear in confessing faith. In John 12:42, believers are hesitant to confess Jesus due to fear of expulsion, while in Matthew 26:69-75, Peter denies knowing Jesus out of fear of association.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 43, 43, 5, 44, 44, 'the praise of men', 'Honor and Praise Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between seeking human honor and divine approval. John 12:43 highlights the preference for human praise, while John 5:44 questions belief when one seeks honor from others instead of God.', 'theme', 0.51, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 43, 40, 23, 5, 7, 'the praise of men', 'Praise of Men vs. God', 'Both passages emphasize the desire for human approval over divine approval. John 12:43 states that some loved ''the praise of men,'' while Matthew 23:5-7 describes actions done ''to be seen of men.''', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 43, 42, 16, 15, 15, 'the praise of men', 'Praise of Men vs. God', 'Both passages emphasize the conflict between seeking human approval and God''s judgment. They highlight that valuing what is esteemed by men can lead to spiritual condemnation.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 43, 47, 10, 18, 18, 'the praise of men', 'Praise and Approval in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of divine approval over human praise. John 12:43 highlights the danger of valuing human commendation, while 2 Corinthians 10:18 asserts that true approval comes from the Lord.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 43, 52, 2, 6, 6, 'the praise of men', 'Praise of Men vs. God', 'Both passages emphasize the contrast between seeking human approval and divine approval. John 12:43 highlights a love for the praise of men, while 1 Thessalonians 2:6 states that glory from men was not sought.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 43, 42, 19, 17, 17, 'the praise of God', 'Faithfulness and Approval', 'This connection highlights the contrast between seeking human approval and being rewarded for faithfulness. While John 12:43 speaks to the desire for human praise, Luke 19:17 emphasizes the reward for those who are faithful, suggesting that true approval comes from God.', 'theme', 0.356, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 43, 9, 2, 30, 30, 'the praise of men', 'Honor and Praise Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of honoring God over seeking human approval. John 12:43 highlights a preference for human praise, while 1 Samuel 2:30 contrasts honoring God with being lightly esteemed.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 44, 40, 10, 40, 40, 'believeth on me, believeth not on me', 'Connection of Belief and Reception', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between belief in Jesus and acceptance of God the Father. They highlight that receiving one is intrinsically linked to receiving the other, establishing a chain of belief and acceptance.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 12, 44, 43, 5, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Belief in God', 'Both passages emphasize belief in the one who sent Jesus. John 12:44 states that believing in Jesus is ultimately believing in God, while John 5:24 highlights that belief in God grants everlasting life.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
